      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>''When the Well Runs Dry'' (May 12) nicely summarized what happens to groundwater supplies during droughts. Since last year's drought, recent rains have filled many lakes and reservoirs. But not all groundwater wells have recovered as fully.</p>
        <p>During the past six rainy weeks, the groundwater level in a monitored well at Hyde Park's Vanderbilt Mansion rose only six inches and remains below long-term average levels.</p>
        <p>Such modest recovery provides an instructive example of how only a fraction of precipitation ever reaches aquifers, and how the arrival of spring hinders aquifer recharge since plants use a significant fraction of rainfall.</p>
        <p>For fuller recovery this year, many aquifers in our region needed more rain, especially during leafless periods in late autumn and early spring.</p>
        <p>There is a continuing risk that wells will run dry this summer, which homeowners and municipal leaders should not ignore.</p>
        <p>RUSSELL URBAN-MEAD  Hydrogeologist  The Chazen Companies  Hyde Park</p>
      </block>
